node.text: comment a “🍓” if you watched my new youtube video I uploaded last night 🥺 Been working on myself a lot lately. I’m trying to wake up earlier, not be scared to say no to plans, and be more assertive. A huge goal for 2021 was to be a lot more assertive. It’s really hard for me, I learned from a young young age that standing up for myself would result in something bad. When you’re a little kid standing up to an adult, there’s a power in-balance. I’m unlearning a fear of being heard. So much of what I go through is related. With ED Recovery, I learn to take up space. I learn to take care of myself and to put myself first. With feeling more open with showing more of my age and the fact that I’m an adult, I learn that I don’t need to infantilize myself to be more “digestible” to other people. Anyways, I love you!! :) This time I’m asking you for advice. How do you feel more comfortable with confrontation and advocating for yourself? Yours truly, Jessie

node.text: literally so weird when people call me a slut because of what I wear?? I love my body for the first time in a while and I love to show that and somehow that represents how much sex I have?? When a man shows his abs he’s fucking applauded?? it’s 2021, get over it! I’m 22 years old. 90% of you that follow me are used to a Jessie that’s ill. That’s SO HARD for me to comprehend on a daily basis. So I want to show off what I worked hard for and continue to work hard for, which is recovery 🥺

node.text: ✨hello, it’s ur girl, jessie✨I’m trying to practice gratitude more often when things are stressful, but sometimes it’s better to just acknowledge something is difficult. I have to do A LOT ALONE. Moving, a lot of stressful career changes, and trying to take care of myself, fender, etc. and be active on here, it’s been IMPOSSIBLE.I think I don’t give myself enough credit. I continued to post and never took a break even when I recovered from an eating disorder ALONE only ONE YEAR AGO. So, when people talk about my views being low and so on, it hurts, because it was so hard to prioritize myself during that time and there were still so many ways I should have prioritized myself more. Long story short, I think I’m doing a good job. There’s so much going on and the amount of stuff I HAVE done and HAVE been strong through…it’s impressive. Anyways, give yourself credit! I really need to stop apologizing for things that aren’t my fault. That’s my next goal. Love, Jessie 🥺❤️

node.text:
(tw: trauma, mental illness) Wanted to educate a bit about BPD (Borderline Personality Disorder)! It’s weird, feeling like you have so many labels. People with BPD commonly struggle with multiple mental illnesses. I definitely haven’t felt this way my whole life. There was a switch and I had some trauma that changed the way I acted. I was scared everyone in my life was going to leave me. I get in these states where I lose control of myself. I text things “out of emotion” that I regret the next day, even post things online. I’m currently working on it a lot. I’m trying to be self aware. What’s really helped me, is learning that I’m allowed to communicate. If I don’t communicate, I end of “exploding” later on and losing control of myself. I’ve also been working on realizing that people aren’t black and white. If you were to ask me, why? It’s something that’s “protective”. You get to a point where you’ve experienced so much and any time you get hurt, you leave the whole situation instead of trying to fix it. I’ve been working on this!! Being self aware is key. You need to realize that some of these protective layers you’ve built up…they’re hurting you. Just a rant. We’re not bad people. I think it’s hardest on ourselves. Anyways, I hope this helps someone out :) Love, Jessie

Photo shared by Jessie Paege on July 03, 2021 tagging @understandingbpd. May be an image of text that says '1. Fear of being hurt again. Many people with BPD are survivors of interpersonal trauma, such as abuse, neglect, bullying, etc., and it's completely understandable to want to avoid the possibility of past trauma repeating. Past adverse or traumatic experiences with people can make being around others triggering, terrifying and exhausting.'.

Photo shared by Jessie Paege on July 03, 2021 tagging @understandingbpd. May be an image of text that says '2. Fear of hurting others. Because we're prone to Splitting on people, or pushing others away because we're afraid they don't care about or they will leave us, or because of many other ways that BPD may have led to us hurting others, many people with BPD have a fear of being close to people again in case we hurt them. We don't intend to hurt anyone, but it can be extremely distressing for us when we do, and we may find it safer, as a result, to keep people at a distance.'.

node.text: hello! life is rly rly rly hard right now and I’m so sorry I’ve been so bad with posting the last year. I had three years of not letting myself watch TV without working at the same time or needing to take a picture in EVERY moment and I completely got burnt out. Then, when I moved across the country and we were all staying at home, I finally got to do the things I never cared to do. I got to date and learn about what’s a HEALTHY relationship. I had friendships and moments that weren’t public. I formed a skincare routine and recovered from my ED. Yet, I feel so guilty? I feel like I’m letting everyone down. It’s my worst fear coming true, why I never stopped working. I don’t regret it, but I know a lot of you have stuck with me through this and it’s very appreciated. I promise, I’ll get back to a (healthier) version of who I used to be and you’ll see my face more! Love, jessie
